Edit `platform/mcp-server/src/mcp-setup.ts` in the `tools/list` handler (lines 136-146). When building the tools array for plugin tools, look up the plugin from `state.plugins` to get its `trustTier`, then prepend the appropriate tag to the description.

The plugin data is in `state.plugins` (a Map<string, RegisteredPlugin>). RegisteredPlugin has a `trustTier` field (type TrustTier from shared). Add a small helper:

```typescript
const trustTierPrefix = (tier: TrustTier): string => {
  switch (tier) {
    case 'official': return '[Official] ';
    case 'community': return '[Community plugin — unverified] ';
    case 'local': return '[Local plugin] ';
  }
};
```

Then in the loop: `description: trustTierPrefix(plugin.trustTier) + toolDef.description`.

This is a read-time transformation — the stored manifest descriptions are not modified.

Two changes:

1. `platform/mcp-server/src/manifest-schema.ts`: Add `.max(1000)` to the tool description field (line 13: `z.string().min(1).max(1000, 'Tool description must be at most 1000 characters')`). Add `.max(500)` to the plugin description field (line 22: `z.string().min(1).max(500, 'Plugin description must be at most 500 characters')`).

2. `platform/mcp-server/src/discovery.ts`: After `loadPluginFromDir` succeeds (around line 134-143), iterate over `manifest.tools` and check each `description` for references to browser tool names. Use a simple check:

```typescript
const BROWSER_TOOL_NAMES = ['browser_execute_script', 'browser_list_tabs', 'browser_open_tab', 'browser_close_tab', 'browser_navigate_tab'];
for (const tool of manifest.tools) {
  for (const btName of BROWSER_TOOL_NAMES) {
    if (tool.description.toLowerCase().includes(btName)) {
      log.warn(`Plugin "${pluginName}" tool "${tool.name}" description references browser tool "${btName}" — possible prompt injection attempt`);
    }
  }
}
```

Place this check inside `loadPluginFromDir` after manifest parsing and URL pattern validation, but before returning the RegisteredPlugin object.

Edit `platform/cli/src/commands/build.ts` where the IIFE wrapper is generated. Find the section that generates the adapter registration code (the part that sets `globalThis.__openTabs.adapters[pluginName] = ...`). After the adapter object is assigned, add `Object.freeze()` calls:

```javascript
// After adapter registration:
var __adapter = globalThis.__openTabs.adapters[pluginName];
if (__adapter && __adapter.tools) {
  __adapter.tools.forEach(function(t) { Object.freeze(t); });
  Object.freeze(__adapter.tools);
}
Object.freeze(__adapter);
```

This must happen inside the IIFE wrapper template, not in the plugin source code. The freeze is shallow by default, but freezing the tools array and each tool entry covers the attack surface (isReady, handle, tools[n].handle).

Note: Object.freeze prevents property modification but does NOT prevent deletion via `Reflect.deleteProperty` on the parent (adapters) object. To prevent deletion, also freeze the adapters object itself: `Object.freeze(globalThis.__openTabs.adapters)`. However, this would prevent NEW adapters from being added. Instead, use Object.defineProperty with configurable:false on each adapter entry.

Actually, the simpler and more correct approach: use `Object.defineProperty(globalThis.__openTabs.adapters, pluginName, { value: __adapter, writable: false, configurable: false })` instead of simple assignment. Then freeze the adapter object itself. This prevents both modification and deletion.

IMPORTANT: The teardown flow in `iife-injection.ts` calls `adapter.teardown()` and then `Reflect.deleteProperty(adapters, pName)`. If the property is non-configurable, the delete will fail silently. The IIFE wrapper already has its own teardown-before-register logic (check the generated wrapper code). The extension-side teardown in `iife-injection.ts:201-222` will need to handle the case where delete fails — it should still proceed with re-injection since the new IIFE will overwrite via the wrapper's own teardown logic.

After making changes to the CLI build, rebuild the e2e-test plugin and any other plugin in plugins/ to verify the new IIFE wrapper works: `cd plugins/e2e-test && bun run build`.
